WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.480
So today I'm going to be talking about the role of CAR-T in double refractory CLL patients

00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:05.780
that are ineligible for allogeneic stem cell transplant.

00:00:06.980 --> 00:00:14.180
I have no financial disclosures, but for full disclosure, I am the PI for Transcendent Emory.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:21.040
So just to lay the background, as we know, the introduction of targeted therapies has

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:23.740
changed the treatment landscape for CLL and SLL dramatically.

00:00:24.420 --> 00:00:28.620
However, there remains an unmet need to overcome resistance to currently available therapies

00:00:28.620 --> 00:00:30.360
in patients with relapsed refractory CLL.

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:36.300
Historically, while allogeneic stem cell transplant has provided a curative option for people

00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:41.620
with CLL and SLL, it's oftentimes not an option for many patients due to access, toxicity,

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:44.460
and patient fitness, as this is generally an older population.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:48.580
So in this hard-to-treat population that's ineligible for stem cell transplants, that's

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:51.100
where CAR-T presents a possible and attractive treatment option.

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:55.340
So for the rest of my talk, I'm going to be talking about the development of CAR-T over

